  "body": "Guys it seems that `go` peer produces gaps in responses to `GET_BLOCK_HASHES` message\n\nLet me show you an example.\nAssume we have following blocks\n\n```\nN.   hash=fe36bdcd1bc8f0c4488e0cdefede865e52fcd563d0c3e887b4ef85a4e8f694e5  parentHash=175da96b4e05be9657242023cdc97d85e9f716dddce786bb489e644c0926ce59\nN+1. hash=03eacf6c9792ae9674c0b3cd1b37a4e799c3d19c055e65f3bbe2aee2d773ca08  parentHash=fe36bdcd1bc8f0c4488e0cdefede865e52fcd563d0c3e887b4ef85a4e8f694e5\n```\n\nWe send a message to get `BLOCK_HASHES` for blocks in interval `[K; N]`\n\n```\n16:15:26 [net]  To:   ec2-54-197-80-137.compute-1.amazonaws.com/54.197.80.137:30305   Send:   \n[GET_BLOCK_HASHES bestHash=03eacf6c9792ae9674c0b3cd1b37a4e799c3d19c055e65f3bbe2aee2d773ca08 maxBlocks=10000]\n```\n\nAnd expect that first hash in response will be a hash of block number `N`\nBut first hash in response is a hash of block number `N-1`\n\n```\n16:15:26 [net]  From:   ec2-54-197-80-137.compute-1.amazonaws.com/54.197.80.137:30305   \nRecv:   175da96b4e05be9657242023cdc97d85e9f716dddce786bb489e644c0926ce59\n...\n```\n\nis there correct behavior on our side?\n\nThanks in advance\n",
